	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Here you are some of my impressions, wich are just impressions that may help and nothing ultimate or anything.
<br />
<br />NES pros :
<br />- Hardware easier to understand and hack
<br />- Graphics are simple to made
<br />- It's developpement scene is quite expanded
<br />- This is an overall nice system
<br />
<br />NES cons :
<br />- Few sprites on the screen (especially 8 per line)
<br />- Cartridge hardware can get a headache
<br />- Slow CPU and very time-critical hardware
<br />
<br />SNES pros :
<br />- Better and brighter graphics, including mode 7
<br />- The sound CPU is downright awesome
<br />- This is an overall nice system
<br />- Fewer different "standard" cartridge hardware
<br />
<br />SNES cons :
<br />- It's developpement scene is very restriced
<br />- Communication between CPU and Sound CPU can get annoying and slow (but once the routine are written they are written for good)
<br />- A lot of things behind the SNES are still poorly and inncacurately doccumented, untested, unverified.
<br />- While the graphics are better, it's harder to actually put them in a good use without having doing prior NES developpement.
<br />
<br />GBA pros :
<br />- Developpement scense is very very large
<br />- Can be programmed in C (for people used to windows)
<br />- Better and brigher graphics, including modes similar to SNES' mode 7.
<br />
<br />GBA cons :
<br />- Sound replaying takes incredibly high amount of CPU time as each sample has to be manually mixed and output manually (but once the sound playing routine have been written it has been written for good)
<br />- While the graphics are better, it's harder to actually put them in a good use without having doing prior NES developpement.
<br />- The screen is small

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


